segments.text: Mr. Whitfield, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates and places of their births and death, the place and date of your birth, and the schools you attended before you entered Texas A&M.
Well, my father was James Whitfield, and he was born in Georgia.
I can't tell you exactly when.
Now, where?
My mother was Eliza Whitfield Brown.
She was Eliza Brown, born in Rush County, Texas.
I can't tell you that exactly.
I might figure it back.
I could figure it.
Can we put that at the end of the tape?
Let me do a little figuring.
I don't want to slow the thing up.
Or if you can tell us when they died and how old they were.
Well, my father died in 1922.
He was 82 years old.
My mother died in 1932.
She was 77 years old.
She was a good bit younger than he was.
I was born at Henderson, Texas, January the 12th, 1892.
And you want me to go from there?
Right.
All right.
So when I was just 12, 8 or 9 years old, my parents moved to Tom Green County, a ranch north of San Angelo, and I grew up on that ranch going to school in a horse and buggy
And later they moved into town so we could have the benefit of these.
What was the ranch?
Did the ranch have a name?
No, just James Whitfield Ranch.
James Whitfield.
Your father owned the ranch.
Okay.
Did you have any responsibilities on the ranch as you were growing up?
Oh, just to the normal youngsters growing up.
I rode a horse along with everybody else.
For how many years then did you ride the horse and buggy back and forth to school every day?
I'd say until about four years.
Then you moved into San Angelo.
Moved into San Angelo, yes.
Was your move from Henderson, was it?
From Henderson to San Angelo.
To the ranch in San Angelo.
Was that by train?
By train.
My father used a boxcar to transfer the
as they did in those days, some livestock.
I don't know what it was.
I just don't remember seeing any.
It was a milk cow, probably.
There wasn't any.
What kind of business had he been engaged in in Henderson before he moved to the ranch?
He had formerly been, he had had some sheep business.
He'd been tax collector in Rusk County at one time.
Must have been somewhat of a gamble to give up a steady job, so to speak, as a tax collector or county official to take on a ranch.
Well, primarily he was a rancher, a farmer.
He wanted to get back into that business.
Was San Angelo, or that area, I gather, was a pretty wide-open area?
bleak place, was it?
Well, no.
San Angelo was a fairly good town at that time.
It was small, of course.
But it was wide open, as you say.
They had saloons and honky-tonk and all that.
Then you graduated from San Angelo High School?
No, I took my last two years of high school at Trinity University at Waxahachie.
Why did you choose to do that?
Well, my parents chose it for me.
Was that a larger and better school than San Angelo?
Well, it was Trenton University.
It's at San Antonio now, you know.
And they had what they called the Academy at that time.
It was sub-freshmen.
Well, it would take two years.
They would take you in your junior and senior year of high school.
So that's where I got
my high school and didn't get a diploma.
I just finished the work.
Finished the work.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M?
Oh, I don't know.
I guess growing up on a ranch, I was interested in livestock.
So you had the opportunity.
And I had had an uncle prior to
My mother's brothers attended A&M, but he didn't graduate.
He attended for a year.
So you knew of the agricultural instruction that was available there, and you were going for that.
You said you didn't receive a diploma, so to speak, from Trinity, so you didn't have a diploma when you entered Texas A&M.
What kind of procedure did you go through to
Oh, I don't know if Charles Friely was there then or not, but I took some grades from Trinity with me, not a transcript, but the courses I had taken, they admitted me with that.
You didn't, as the students do today, apply months in advance?
Oh, no.
No, I just showed up down there.
You just showed up in time for registration.
Yeah.
What was your first reaction?
to the school and to the community when you arrived?
Well, that's rather interesting.
Charlie Moran was a fish along with me, and they were working out for football.
And I was Don Lee's freshman.
He was a San Angelo boy.
He was a junior that year.
And he told me that he was in company C, and he told me to get into company C. Well, I went through the mill and got Captain Moses, who was a commandant at that time.

He asked me if I had a preface to company, and I said, yes, sir, C. And I guess I was scared of something, but he put down G. So I went to G, and Don Lee, at that time, we were in Goodman Hall, and we had to go around the south end of Foster Hall.
And there was a bunch of football players, and Don Lee introduced me to them as his fish.
I don't know what he told them, but he invited them to have at it, and they did.
You say Charlie Moran was a fish.
Freshman.
He was a freshman coach.
He was a freshman.
That was his first, 1909 was his first.
First year as coach.
So right after you registered then, the football players kind of worked you over.
Yes, that's right.
but it was kind of a warm reception.
Really a warm reception.
I was ready to go home.
After that, were you still Mr. Lee's fish, even though you were in different companies?
No, I got to be a fish.
The old boy that looked after me was named Lake Robertson.
He was from Bollinger.
which is just this side of San Angelo.
He took me under his wing and guided me, but Don looked after me once in a while.
He'd come by to see how I was getting along.
So primarily if you were somebody's fish, it was an upperclassman in your company.
Yes, that's right.
That sort of activity didn't cross company lines, is the rule.
No.
Were you assigned to Goodwin Hall?
Yes.
Then the first year you were there.
What other dormitories did you live in?
Mitchell.
The first year that Mitchell was occupied, they moved G Company into Mitchell.
And then did you stay in Mitchell the rest of the time?
Just the one year, yes, my senior year.
Your senior year in Mitchell.
What was life like in those dormitories?
Well...
There was lots of fun.
You and Aggie?
No.
Well, you haven't had the experience.
I don't know whether they did it in your age time or not, but we had plenty of hazing going on.
It wasn't wild.
They'd strap you.
Usually they'd have somebody would...
take you and tell you to report after dinner, after supper, every night.
You'd go in and if you were a good fish they'd just slap you once or twice and let you go, but if you were an honorary fish they'd let you have it.
And we had some peanut racers up and down the hall with our noses, you know, somebody
standing by on his drivers, things of that sort.
A couple of fish racing against each other?
Yes.
But it was good life.
It was lots of fun.
Lots of bull sessions?
Oh, yeah.
Of course, at that time, after we got through with supper,
They marched us to our meals, but after we were through eating, we all just straggled on.
And we had to call the quarters at that time.
You had to be in your room, and then they blew an assembly, I guess.
I don't remember what the people's call was.
I believe it was at 7 o'clock or 7.30.
You had to be in your room.
And we had all student government at that time.
And there were no profs or no sergeants or anything in the dorms.
It was all the captain of the company was responsible for the behavior of the fellows in his company.
And we had inspection right after call to quarters to see that you were in your room.
You stayed in there until what we called Tattoo, which was 1015, and then at 1030 we had taps, and you had to have your lights out.
I guess Kerber told you all that, didn't he?
Well, he was pretty much the same when he was there.
Did you take it a sentry walking the hallways during the flight hour?
Yeah.
And we all stood guard, all the privates.
walked post in the different dormitories, and we had an officer of the day from the corps, the sergeant of the guard, and the corporal of the guard.
Now was this all day?
No, just at night.
Just during the quiet hours?
Of course, the officer of the day and the sergeant of the guard were all day long, but the sentries were just at night, to walk post during the study hour.
When somebody was assigned as officer of the day, was he in the quarters all day then?
Or did he have to leave when he went to class?
He was in the guard room all day or whatever it was.
I think it was a guard room.
But he had to make inspections of the rooms to see that the beds were made and that they were clean.
Well, if he was officer of the day, then was he excused from classes for that day?
Oh, yes.
Yes.
This was done on a rotating basis, I would gather.
Yes.
So you would be officer of the day only a couple of times, I suppose, in a turn.
Probably.
I just don't recall how often.
Okay.
What kind of activity did you have right after you got up?
I mean, you were awakened by the bugle?
Bugle.
We did everything to the bugle.
We had revelry.
We got out and did calisthenics.
For about how long?
Oh, 10 minutes, I'd say.
And then you do what?
Dress, shave, dress.
Went over and assembled for breakfast.
And they marched us to breakfast.
And as I say, after we finished eating, we just wandered back to quarters.
and then getting ready to go to class.
Yes.
And sometime during the day, this man that was officer of the day would inspect your quarters to make sure that they were made properly.
And everything was cleaned up.
The floor was clean.
The GI bucket was... We had that in Goodwin Hall.
In Mitchell, we had a little different proposition.
A little better.
You had a regular bathroom?
Yeah, we had showers.
We had to go to Natler, Goodman Hall, to get our baths.
Well, Goodman Hall was then a fairly new dormitory, wasn't it?
It didn't have any showers.
That's right.
No, we went to Natler until, well, fall of 1912 when we went to Mitchell Hall.
I don't know what they did in Goodman Hall after that.
Because it seemed to me that the old natatorium that they called it was the one with the steam plant.
It wasn't a natatorium, it was just showers.
They called it the natatorium.
But it seemed to me that it was closed right about fall of 1912.
Did they require you to take a shower regularly, or did you just, was that?
No, it was voluntary.
It was voluntary.
Yeah, because you were inspected regularly, so you had to keep clean.
I ask that partly because I recently read some letters written by a fellow who was there in the 1880s, and he indicated that he bathed regularly, but one of the other boys

had been taken to the doctor because he was quite ill, and the doctor asked him about how often he bathed, and the boy said he had bathed twice since he'd been there, about two and a half months, and both of those were in the first week.
Yeah.
I mean, he was smelling the high heaven with it.
I would imagine he was, yeah.
About how much time did you spend drilling?
On a daily basis, or did you drill daily?
No, we drilled every Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays.
For an hour, I believe.
I believe that's right.
Did you have classes on Saturday as well as the other day?
Saturday morning.
Saturday afternoon was fairly free then?
Free, yeah.
Okay.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Well, I enjoyed it.
It was good.
I'll never forget the coconut pie.
I was a fish, and I remarked how much I liked coconut pie, and there were two pies on the table, and I ate them both.
That must have been something for a fish to get two whole pies.
Well, they made me eat them.
The sophomores are sort of that.
Did they not like them?
Oh, no, they just wanted me to have all the pie I wanted.
Normally it's the other way around, isn't it?
The upperclassmen get the cushion.
That's right.
They get the cushion.
I just made the remark, boy, there's some coconut pie, and I sure do like it.
Fish, you really like coconut pie.
Yeah, well, just eat both of these pies.
At a normal table, I realized that the company ate together.
Now, obviously, the whole company couldn't get it at one table.
About how many people would be at the table?
No.
We had two sophomores at each table.
They sat at the end, the corporals.
And as I recall, we had about 14 at the table.
And the company would be, what, about 100?
That or a little less.
Most of the time they were in the 80s too.
So anywhere from six to seven tables would be company.
What privileges did the upperclassmen enjoy that the freshmen didn't have?
A freshman could do most anything that he could get by with, except, you mean so far as the school is concerned now?
Yeah.
Freshman didn't have many privileges in the dorm, because the upperclassmen saw that he was kept in line.
That was part of his training.
But a freshman couldn't go to town, couldn't go to Bryan,
once every month or something like that.
That would be only on a Saturday afternoon.
Yeah, on a Saturday afternoon.
Or maybe Sunday, I don't know.
I'd have to go to Brian on Sunday.
I seldom went on Saturdays.
Was the Tunerville trolley working or in operation?
It was a motor-driven bus my senior year.
What was it?
It was none in existence before that at all?
How would you get to Bryan before that?
Either walk or ride a freight train.
Ride a freight train.
Didn't the passenger train stop in?
No, it wasn't until the proper time.
Yeah, they stopped at College Station, the INGN and H&TC, too.
They both came through at that time.
I don't know if they still do or not, do they?
Well, they still have the tracks there.
They come through as freight trains, I believe.
But those trains, it was not convenient to take those.
No, the hours weren't convenient to take into Bryan.
But you could hop, could hop a freight.
Could hop a freight.
Or walk.
Or walk.
It's about a, what, five-mile hike?
About a five-mile hike.
Into what would have been downtown Bryan.
Yeah.
What, for what purposes did the students go to Bryan?
Oh, just to go to town, more or less, I think.
Wade Cox had a pool hall that got quite a play, all right.
I don't know if you've ever heard of Wade Cox's pool hall.
No, never heard of Wade Cox's pool hall.
He had a pool hall that got a lot of play, and the Harry Jenkins Bar got a little play, too.
I don't know if you've heard of his place.
No.
Maybe I'm talking too much.
No, you're not talking too much.
I don't know, in those days the cadets could go in and get a nigger to get them some beer or something.
I should say a black or colored person, rather.
But they went to Brown to, they probably, some fellows had girls who they knew that they wanted to call on, particularly upperclassmen.
But the freshmen, they didn't have anybody.
They didn't have any cause to go to Bryan, really, truly.
As far as anything that they needed for school, I presume that was available on campus, probably.
Oh, yes.
So we wouldn't have to go to Bryan to buy things.
What was that bohemian that made the uniforms?
I had the uniforms.
Charlie... Mitchie?
Mitchie, yeah.
He made the uniforms and had everything that you needed in the way of clothing.
Where was his shop?
I don't recall.
It seemed to me it was in the, to the left.
That's the present Nassau, the old Spieser Hall, the present Spieser Hall.
It was the left and back of it a little, as I recall.
Of course, not too far from Gathright Hall.
Let's see, the Y was not built until after you, was not completed until after you graduated, was it?
That's right.
We had just a basement, as I think.
So there was a basement portion of it completed while you were there.
What was available down there?
Oh, not much of anything.
Not much of anything, no.
Did you have any kind of place where students could gather socially?
Oh, we had an old barn for a gym.
I don't think they even had a name for it, as I recall.
Just a gym?
Just a gym.
Okay.
Was that where the basketball team played?
Did intramural basketball play there, too?
There wasn't any intramural basketball.
There was intramural baseball and football.
Basketball didn't come in until later, did it?
No.
I was managing the first basketball team A&M ever had.
That is, of the college basketball team?
Yeah.
I believe, let's see, you were there when both the Old Main and the
original mess hall burning, weren't you?
I was a fireman.
You fought the fire.
Bucket Brigade.
I imagine that was quite something, wasn't it?
Oh, it was.
The mess hall, as I recall, burned just before Christmas, and they had us go home a little early.
We came back, and they had an old contonement built in the fetus there.
A what?
A contonement, kind of a ramshackle.
Army-type structure, you know, for emergencies.
So that's where you ate until?
Until Spieser was finished.
Spieser was finished.
It was finished forgosh, it waswhen did it burn?
I've forgotten.
Was it in the spring of 12?
I believe so, yeah.
Old Main burned in 11, I believe, in Mesa.
Mesa burned before Main did.
Mesa burned first, and then Main.
Yeah.
That's not much difference, I don't suppose.
We have a number of pictures of the old Main building during the fire, and some of the walls there are still left.
How did they tear down the walls?
Or do you recall?
I don't recall.
I don't believe they'd torn them down one night.
Yes, they bound to have torn them down before I graduated.
Because I believe they started the new building on the same location and completed it by 14.
Had they?
Yeah.
So the new one was probably being constructed your final year there.
Did the cadet officers enjoy any particular privileges that were not available to the other cadets?
No.
You mentioned, say, in the mess hall that you had a corporal at either end of the table.
Where did the other company officers eat?
They were scattered around in there and all through the tables.
Did they not eat with the company?
Oh, yes.
Yes.
What about the regimental officers?
Did they eat?
They had a staff table.
Staff table.
Yeah.
They were privileged.
They got steaks and things like that.
So the regimental officers had better food than you did.
Yes, they did, yes.
Was the same true for the athletes?
Oh, yeah.
The same table was a good place to eat.
Well, when you were manager of the basketball team, did you get to eat with the athletes?
You bet, you bet.
That was a good incentive for being in.
Oh, yeah.
That's your watch.
Uh-huh.
Now, on this training table, did the athletes eat there the whole year or just while they were participating?
Just during their season.
Did the athletes have any other privileges other than the training table?
No.
They had to, when they weren't practicing, would have to do their regular drills?
No, they didn't.
Well, yeah, I'll take it back now.
The football team and the baseball team, as I recall, didn't drill, but the basketball team did, because theywait a minute, I'm not right about that.
I was captain of the Chief Company, and I was the manager of the basketball team, so I'm bound to have drilled.
I had to be with my company.
So all companies drilled at the same time?
Yeah.
See, we just had three battalions, twelve companies.
The parade ground took care of it pretty well.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Well, yeah, I guess so.
I guess you'd call Dr. Mark Francis one of my favorites.
What did you particularly like about him?
John Burns.
What did you particularly like about Dr. Francis?
Well, he was a good instructor, good teacher, and a rare character, if there ever was one.
Is it all right if I tell you a little incident?
Sure, let me make sure I have enough tape here on this side.
Yeah, I believe so.
Well, we had a fellow named Frank Lockridge in our company, and we had
The vet science was taught was kind of an amphitheater.
Frank would always sit over there in the open window and chew tobacco.
Doc Francis got up one day and picked up a GI bucket and took it up there and put it down.
He said, hey, Rube's spitting that.
So he was Rube Lockridge from then on.
Dr. Francis was quite a character.
He was a wonderful man, and then John Burns, he was a prophet of the age.
He was a good one.
Bobby Smith, math prof. Carby Cameron tried to teach me some French, and it didn't take too well.
I know what you mean.
I had some French in the graduate school.
Is that right?
Well, Carby would try to get me to say the feminine of one, you know, U-N-E.
I'd say, eun, and he'd say, no, it's not that, it's eun.
I couldn't get to suit him at all.
Well, the kind of French I took was not really so much in speaking but in translating.
We were supposed to learn a few words, though, and they were just beyond me.
Between my English and my German, I couldn't make those French words sound right.
